<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-211-052  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 211 052.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  April 24 1989 v23 n17 p23(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A programming catch-22. (object-oriented programming languages andstandardization)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gibson, Stanley.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Object-oriented languages such as ATandamp;T's C++ are not yet matureenough to undergo formal standardization, but wide-spread progressin the object-oriented programming field may be hindered by a lackof standards.andP;  Users should develop several more years ofexperience with the language before standards are considered.andP;  Anew version of C++ is due out by Jun 30, 1989.andP;  In addition to animproved reference manual which has been completely rewritten,multiple inheritance capability has been added to the language.andO;Multiple inheritance will allow an object to take traits from morethan one superior class.andP;  The new version may also be bettersupported by ATandamp;T.andP;  C++ is a derivative of C programming language,which is included as a subset, allowing a programmer to switchback and forth between object-oriented and C.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Object-Oriented LanguagesStandardizationApplicationsC Programming Language.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>